 "aspect_ratio": 0.56, "filesize_approx": 1937996, "http_headers": {"User-Agent": "Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/95.0.4638.17 Safari/537.36", "Accept": "text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8", "Accept-Language": "en-us,en;q=0.5", "Sec-Fetch-Mode": "navigate", "Referer": "https://www.instagram.com/"}, "video_ext": "mp4", "audio_ext": "none", "abr": 0, "vbr": 955.09, "format": "dash-1278213400711452v - 1080x1920 (DASH video)"}], "title": "Video by musicallyproper", "description": "In 1982, Conrad Schnitzler—once a member of Tangerine Dream and Kluster—dropped ‘The Shark Eats Ice.’ A track so icy, mechanical, and satirical it feels like electroclash 20 years early.\n\nSchnitzler came from Berlin’s art-school avant-garde, where Dada thrived on absurd, vivid phrases that stripped words of rational meaning. \n\nBorn during WWI, Dada was an anti-art movement that embraced nonsense and provocation as a way to reject logic and convention. \n\n‘The Shark Eats Ice’ feels like exactly that—a machine-beat predator devouring something cold and empty, a surreal title that mirrors the track’s satire of consumer electronics and the dehumanizing chill of machine culture.\n\n(Visuals by the synth performance art pioneers, Tik and Tok)\n\n#conradschnitzler #electro #electroclash #synthmusic #mimes", "duration": 16.233, "timestamp": 1757079367, "uploader_id": "52091227214", "uploader": "MP", "channel": "musicallyproper", "like_count": 31393, "comment_count": 421, "comments": [{"author": "mkultra360", "author_id": "4744865568", "id": "17883922017452846", "text": "@queenofthecasshole you & I walking off the flugzeug after finally getting around to visiting Berlin.", "timestamp": 1772132396}, {"author": "chantoshii", "author_id": "45397495218", "id": "17855803911656141", "text": "😍😍😍", "timestamp": 1771347410}, {"author": "obliviawerbesprache", "author_id": "9195490115", "id": "17842434039696315", "text": "